&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Deoxyribonucleic acid&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Deoxyribonucleic acid (DNA) serves as the primary information source for making proteins in the cell.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;DNA contains the genetic instructions necessary for the development, functioning, and reproduction of all known living organisms and many viruses.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The sequences of nucleotides in DNA are transcribed into messenger RNA (mRNA) which is then translated into protein by ribosomes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;DNA is composed of two strands that coil around each other to form a double helix, carrying the genetic instructions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;DNA replication is essential for cell division, ensuring that each new cell receives an exact copy of the DNA.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ribonucleic acid (RNA)&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;RNA is involved in various roles such as coding, decoding, regulation, and expression of genes.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Messenger RNA (mRNA) conveys genetic information from DNA to the ribosome, where it directs protein synthesis.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Proteins&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Proteins are large, complex molecules that play many critical roles in the body, such as catalyzing metabolic reactions and DNA replication.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They are made up of amino acids and are essential for the structure, function, and regulation of the body&amp;#39;s tissues and organs.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Genes&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Genes are segments of DNA that carry hereditary information and are responsible for guiding the process of creating proteins.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Each gene provides instructions for making a specific protein or set of proteins.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Flagellates.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Flagellates &lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;are found in the bottom of a pond.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;They&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;are&amp;nbsp;an example of&amp;nbsp;Protozoa.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Protozoa&amp;nbsp;are found in&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;soil, freshwater, and seawater.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Some are found in the body of other organisms and are&amp;nbsp;pathogenic. These are&amp;nbsp;unicellular organisms with eukaryotic cells.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;There is great variation in cell structure, organs of locomotion and modes of nutrition among protozoa.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These organisms reproduce by&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;simple cell division.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Zooplankton &lt;/strong&gt;is present on the&amp;nbsp;second trophic level&amp;nbsp;in a&amp;nbsp;food chain&amp;nbsp;in the&amp;nbsp;aquatic ecosystem.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are&amp;nbsp;primary consumers&amp;nbsp;as they eat&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;phytoplankton&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;(producers) and are themselves in turn eaten by small fishes (secondary consumers).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Jellyfish &lt;/strong&gt;and sea jellies are the informal common names given to the medusa-phase of certain gelatinous members of the subphylum Medusozoa, a major part of the phylum Cnidaria.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Cells&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Cells are the basic structural and functional units of all living organisms.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They can exist as independent single-celled organisms or as part of a multicellular organism.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Cells carry out essential processes such as metabolism, energy conversion, and reproduction.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;There are two main types of cells: prokaryotic cells, which do not have a defined nucleus, and eukaryotic cells, which have a defined nucleus and organelles.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Cells are composed of various organelles that perform specific functions necessary for the cell&amp;#39;s survival and proper functioning.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Tissues&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Tissues are groups of similar cells that work together to perform a specific function.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;There are four basic types of tissues in animals: epithelial, connective, muscle, and nervous tissues.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Organs&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Organs are structures made up of different types of tissues that work together to perform specific functions within an organism.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Examples include the heart, lungs, and brain in animals, and roots, stems, and leaves in plants.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Organ Systems&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Organ systems are groups of organs that work together to perform complex functions necessary for the survival of the organism.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Examples of organ systems in animals include the circulatory system, respiratory system, and digestive system.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is the&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Microwave&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A microwave oven uses microwaves to heat food&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the case of microwave ovens, the commonly used &lt;strong&gt;radio wave frequency is roughly 2,500 megahertz (2.5 gigahertz)&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Radio waves in this frequency range absorbed by water, fats, and sugars. When they are absorbed they are converted directly into atomic motion or vibration.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore heavy motion or vibration is converted into heat.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Microwaves are not absorbed by most plastics, glass, or ceramics.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The frequency of the Microwave equals the resonance frequency of water. Therefore foods could be heated up by the oscillation of water molecules.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;An &lt;strong&gt;Electric heater, Electric blub (with filament), Electric iron is the electrical device that converts an electric current into heat&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They working on the principle of the Joule heating effect.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;An electric current passing through a resistor will convert that electrical energy into heat energy.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;an acceleration&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When an object falls under gravity, it experiences an acceleration due to the gravitational force exerted by the Earth.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This acceleration is called gravitational acceleration and is denoted by &amp;#39;g&amp;#39;, which is approximately 9.8 m/s&amp;sup2; near the Earth&amp;#39;s surface.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Gravitational acceleration acts on all objects equally, regardless of their masses.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The direction of the acceleration is towards the center of the Earth.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;During free fall, the only force acting on the object is gravity, making it an ideal example of uniformly accelerated motion.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Gravitational Force&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Gravitational force is the attractive force between two masses.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is one of the four fundamental forces of nature.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The strength of the gravitational force between two objects depends on their masses and the distance between them.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Free Fall&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Free fall is the motion of a body where gravity is the only force acting upon it.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In a vacuum, all objects fall at the same rate regardless of their mass.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Terminal Velocity&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Terminal velocity is the constant speed that a freely falling object eventually reaches when the resistance of the medium prevents further acceleration.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;At terminal velocity, the force of gravity is balanced by the drag force of the medium.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ethylene is helpful in the ripening of natural fruit.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is a gaseous compound naturally produced by the plants to promote ageing and maturity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is produced by manufacturers and used to ripen the fruits.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Chemicals such as calcium carbide are used to ripen the fruits in order to attain maturity faster in comparison to ethylene gas, as it may cause health issues.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mg&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Magnesium (Mg) is more reactive towards dilute hydrochloric acid compared to aluminum (Al), zinc (Zn), and iron (Fe).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When magnesium reacts with dilute hydrochloric acid, it produces hydrogen gas and forms magnesium chloride:&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\( \text{Mg} + 2\text{HCl} \rightarrow \text{MgCl}_2 + \text{H}_2 \)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This reaction is faster and more vigorous than the reactions of Al, Zn, and Fe with dilute hydrochloric acid.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Magnesium is higher in the reactivity series compared to aluminum, zinc, and iron, making it more reactive.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Reactivity Series&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The reactivity series is a series of metals arranged in order of decreasing reactivity.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It helps to predict how metals will react with acids, water, and other substances.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hydrogen Gas Test&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Hydrogen gas can be tested by bringing a lit splint near the mouth of the test tube; a &amp;#39;pop&amp;#39; sound confirms the presence of hydrogen.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Reactions of Other Metals&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Aluminum reacts with dilute hydrochloric acid to form aluminum chloride and hydrogen gas, but it is less vigorous due to the formation of a protective oxide layer.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Zinc reacts more readily than iron but less than magnesium, forming zinc chloride and hydrogen gas.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Iron reacts with dilute hydrochloric acid to form iron(II) chloride and hydrogen gas, but the reaction is slower compared to magnesium and zinc.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Option &lt;strong&gt;4&lt;/strong&gt; is correct, i.e. &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Good Conductor&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Resistance&lt;/strong&gt;: It&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;is the opposition that a substance offers to the flow of electric current.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The resistance of the conductor depends on:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;its length&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;on its area of cross-section&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;on the nature of its material.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;R = &amp;rho;l /A wherein R is Resistance,&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;rho; is resistivity, l is the length of the conductor, A is the area of cross-section.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The symbol of resistance is &lt;strong&gt;Ω&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;and its unit is the&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;ohm.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;​&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Conductivity&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;: electrical conductivity&amp;nbsp;is the ability of&amp;nbsp;electric&amp;nbsp;current to flow through a material. Its unit is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;mho&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Silver&amp;nbsp;is a natural element which&amp;nbsp;has high conductivity and low resistivity.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Pumice&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Pumice is a correct example of foam in colloids.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Foam is a type of colloid where gas is dispersed in a solid or liquid medium.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Pumice forms when gas bubbles are trapped in solidified lava, creating a porous structure.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This porous nature of pumice makes it light and able to float on water.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Other examples of foam include whipped cream (gas in liquid) and Styrofoam (gas in solid).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mist&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Mist is an example of a colloid where liquid droplets are dispersed in a gas (air).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is commonly seen when tiny water droplets are suspended in the air, reducing visibility.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Jelly&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Jelly is a colloid where a liquid is dispersed in a solid medium.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is a semi-solid substance used in various food products.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Fog&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Fog is similar to mist but consists of larger water droplets dispersed in the air.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is a dense layer of water droplets that decreases visibility significantly.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is option &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt; i.e&amp;nbsp;&lt;b&gt;&lt;u&gt;Convex&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The convex lens&lt;/strong&gt; generally bends inwards when the ray of light falls on it.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The convex lens is a lens that converges rays of light that convey &lt;strong&gt;parallel to its principal axis&lt;/strong&gt;, which is relatively thick across the middle and thin at the lower and upper edges.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Some of the uses of the convex lens are :
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is used&amp;nbsp;for the lenses of a person suffering from &lt;strong&gt;long-sightedness (Hypermetropia).&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is used in &lt;strong&gt;microscopes, telescopes, and magnifying glasses&lt;/strong&gt; to subject all the light to a specific object.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is used in&lt;strong&gt; camera lens&lt;/strong&gt; because they focus light on&amp;nbsp;a clear picture.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A convex lens is also known as the &lt;strong&gt;converging lens&lt;/strong&gt; because it converges a parallel beam of light on a point called the principal focus.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Some of the uses of other lenses are:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

